    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-01-27T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-01-27T05:00:00-05:00" n="3"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d3">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/27514: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-01-27T17:00:00+07:00"
                            >January 27, 1943—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received January 27—1:44 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>148. A message from our Embassy [in] London received last night stated joint
                    message from President and Churchill for Generalissimo<note n="5" xml:id="d3fn5"
                        >Telegram of January 25, <hi rend="italic">supra</hi>.</note> was being
                    communicated through British Ambassador<note n="5a" xml:id="d3fn7">Sir Horace
                        James Seymour.</note> with whom by President’s direction I should arrange
                    for immediate joint delivery.<note n="6" xml:id="d3fn6">See communiqué of
                        January 26, Department of State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, January 30,
                        1943, p. 93.</note> Message was not received by my British colleague until
                    this morning and we made joint delivery shortly after noon. Generalissimo asked
                    us to convey his thanks respectively to President and Churchill. He made no
                    comment. Foreign Minister<note n="6a" xml:id="d3fn8">T. V. Soong.</note> who was
                    present said that undoubtedly Generalissimo’s reply would go forward later.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
